and slaves, some of whom were eventually transported overseas.The evidence that most New World creoles were imports traceable to West Africa strongly suggests that the well-established limited access model for plantation creole needs revision. In forcing a reexamination of this basic tenet, McWhorter's book will undoubtedly cause controversy. At the same time, it makes available a vast amount of data that will be a valuable resource for further explorations of genesis theory.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplezAfrica, WestxLanguages. 0aBlacksxLanguagesxAfrica, West. 0aCreole dialectsxHistoryxCaribbean Area. 0aCreole dialectszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aLangues créolesxHistoirexCaraïbes (Région). 0aNoirsxLanguesxAfrique occidentalexAfrica, WestxCaribbean Area. 0aPidgin languagesxHistory. 0aPidgins (Langues)xHistoire. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aSemiotics & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aMcWhorter, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021999140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092349240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923492/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles